    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-02T13:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-02T13:36:00-05:00" n="1024"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1024">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/299.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-02T12:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 2, 1912—12 noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your March 25, 4 p.m. The Government has agreed to take entire Chargé of shipment
                    of American arms from Vera Cruz, furnishing a Federal guard therefor. Minister
                    of Hacienda thinks the usual duty should be paid. Under the circumstances it
                    perhaps ought to be waived, but I think it good policy to accede and pay the
                    duty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
